04786nam a22006255i 9780226777887DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020046180  a97802267778877 a10.7208/97802267778872doi  a(DE-B1597)582459  a(OCoLC)1247671235  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aRC450.F7bR63 2021 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aRobcis, Camille, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisalienation :bPolitics, Philosophy, and Radical Psychiatry in Postwar France /cCamille Robcis. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b24 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in Practices of Meaning00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. A Politics of Madness -- tChapter 1. François Tosquelles, Saint-Alban, and the Invention of Institutional Psychotherapy -- tChapter 2. Frantz Fanon, the Pathologies of Freedom, and the Decolonization of Institutional Psychotherapy -- tChapter 3. Félix Guattari, La Borde, and the Search for Anti- oedipal Politics -- tChapter 4. Michel Foucault, Psychiatry, Antipsychiatry, and Power -- tEpilogue. The Hospital as a Laboratory of Political Invention -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1940 to 1945, forty thousand patients died in French psychiatric hospitals. The Vichy regime’s “soft extermination” let patients die of cold, starvation, or lack of care. But in Saint-Alban-sur-Limagnole, a small village in central France, one psychiatric hospital attempted to resist. Hoarding food with the help of the local population, the staff not only worked to keep patients alive but began to rethink the practical and theoretical bases of psychiatric care. The movement that began at Saint-Alban came to be known as institutional psychotherapy and would go on to have a profound influence on postwar French thought. In Disalienation, Camille Robcis grapples with the historical, intellectual, and psychiatric meaning of the ethics articulated at Saint-Alban by exploring the movement’s key thinkers, including François Tosquelles, Frantz Fanon, Félix Guattari, and Michel Foucault. Anchored in the history of one hospital, Robcis's study draws on a wide geographic context—revolutionary Spain, occupied France, colonial Algeria, and beyond—and charts the movement's place within a broad political-economic landscape, from fascism to Stalinism to postwar capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPsychiatryxPhilosophyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychiatryxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aPsychotherapyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ainstitutional psychotherapy, radical psychiatry, psychoanalysis, François Tosquelles, Frantz Fanon, Félix Guattari, Michel Foucault, Jacques Lacan, anti-psychiatry, 20th century French philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226777887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226777887/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACK